<doc id="29321441" url="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=29321441" title="Muhamed Bešić">
Muhamed Bešić

Muhamed Bešić (; born 10 September 1992) is a Bosnian professional footballer who plays as a defensive midfielder for Championship club Middlesbrough, on loan from Everton, and the Bosnia and Herzegovina national team.

Bešić started his professional career at Hamburger SV, playing mainly in its reserve team, before moving to Ferencváros in 2012. Two years later he joined Everton. He was loaned to Middlesbrough in 2018.

A former youth international for Bosnia and Herzegovina, Bešić made his senior international debut in 2010, and is the youngest player ever to represent the country. He made over 30 caps since and represented the nation at their first major tournament, the 2014 FIFA World Cup.

Born in Berlin to Bosnian parents, Bešić joined local club TB Berlin at the age of 14, where he remained until he was 16, when he signed for Hamburger SV. On 4 November 2010, Bešić signed his first professional contract with Hamburger SV until June 2013. He made his professional debut in Bundesliga game against Borussia Dortmund on 12 November 2010 at the age of 18. Bešić came on as a substitute in the 80th minute when Dortmund was already leading 2–0. A week later, he started his first Bundesliga game away at Hannover 96, and played full 90 minutes in a 3–2 loss.

In March 2012, Bešić was suspended from the first team, due to lack of discipline. Bosnian media also claimed that manager Thorsten Fink "strangled" Bešić and threw him out of the dressing room.

In 2012 Bešić was signed by Hungarian club Ferencváros on free transfer. He scored his first and only goal for the club in an away victory over Paksi, which was also his first professional goal. In his first season, he helped the team win Ligakupa by beating MOL Vidi in the final.

In July 2013, Bešić prolonged his contract with Ferencváros until 2016.

On 28 July 2014 Bešić signed a five-year contract with Everton for an undisclosed fee, speculated to be in the region of £4 million. Having been an unused substitute in the first two games of the season, he made his first Premier League appearance on 30 August against Chelsea, replacing Romelu Lukaku in the 89th minute; however he made a defensive error which allowed opponent Diego Costa to score the final goal in a 3–6 home defeat. Bešić made his first start for Everton in the Merseyside derby on 27 September, being substituted after 80 minutes for Samuel Eto'o as the game ended in a 1–1 away draw.

His second season at Everton was plagued by hamstring injuries, which limited his appearances and playing time. In February 2016 he was voted Everton's Player of the Month for January. He also extended his contract until June 2021.

In August 2016, Bešić was ruled out for about six month as he tore anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee. Bešić was slowly making his way back to full fitness as he was involved with Everton Under-23s' in mid-April 2017. He missed the whole 2016–17 campaign, not playing a single minute for Everton, before eventually returning to action coming on as a 77th-minute substitute for his national team on 9 June 2017.

Bešić returned to Premier League action on 21 August 2017, almost 16 months since his last game, in a 1–1 away draw at Manchester City.

After falling out of favor at Everton, in January 2018, Bešić joined Championship club Middlesbrough on loan until the end of the season. He debuted on 17 February against Cardiff City. Bešić scored his first goal for Middlesbrough, which was also his first goal in over four years, against Derby County on 21 April.

Bešić returned to Middlesbrough on a season-long loan in August 2018.

Bešić claimed in an interview that he had declined an offer to play for Germany, because he only wished to play for Bosnia and Herzegovina. He was first part of Bosnia and Herzegovina under-21 side.

On 5 November 2010, Bešić was called-up to the senior team by Safet Sušić for friendly game against Slovakia. He made his debut in that match, thereby becoming the youngest player to ever play for Bosnia and Herzegovina at senior level. The record was previously held by Miralem Pjanić.

Bešić was selected to play for Bosnia and Herzegovina at the 2014 FIFA World Cup, country's first ever major competition. He made his tournament debut in the opening group game, which ended in a narrow loss to Argentina at the Maracanã Stadium,

He was given a straight red card on 6 September 2015, in a 3–0 home win over Andorra in UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying game for throwing his chewing gum at Víctor Rodríguez, who was also sent off for retaliating.

During his career, Bešić has been deployed as a right back and as a centre back, although his natural position by his own words is defensive midfielder.

He was described in 2014 by Everton manager Roberto Martínez as a "very complete footballer", who "has got a very natural balance about knowing that he can be strong and aggressive but in the same way he's a technical player on the ball."

Bešić has many tattoos, his first being the word "Bosanac" (Bosnian). Some of many are also names of his parents and brother. He is a Muslim; along with international team mates Vedad Ibišević and Edin Višća he visited a mosque in Cuiabá during the 2014 FIFA World Cup. On 4 July 2013, he became the Bosnian ambassador for the Emmaus charity organisation.

Bešić has two daughters with his long-time girlfriend Jessica.

